item.title: FAQ
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: [vc_row][vc_column][vc_tta_accordion][vc_tta_section title="What Is the Best Way to Lose Fat?" tab_id="1461246222048-213dc637-9e1f"][vc_column_text]The simple (and complex) answer is that there is no “best way” to lose fat. Each client will respond differently to a training program. However, there are some principles fitness professionals can apply when designing their clients’ programs.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="If I Lift Weights, Will I Get Bigger Muscles?" tab_id="1461246222170-47cf8950-ec4a"][vc_column_text]Whether or not your clients will get bigger muscles (hypertrophy) depends on three basic factors: genetics, gender and training intensity. Genetics is mostly manifested as muscle fiber type; people with predominantly fast-twitch fibers acquire larger muscles more easily than people with predominantly slow-twitch fibers.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="How Do I Get a Flat Stomach?" tab_id="1461246427821-2c8321e9-05e5"][vc_column_text]Genetics also plays a role in whether or not your clients can obtain a flat stomach or a “six-pack” look to their abdominals. Having said that, two types of exercise can help: strength training and cardiovascular exercise. The abdominals are just like any other muscle group: For their definition to become visible, they must grow larger and the fat that lies over them must decrease.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="Should I Do Cardio First or Weight Training First?" tab_id="1461246430877-a99c601c-891e"][vc_column_text]It depends on the client’s goals. Many personal trainers think that performing strength training before cardiovascular exercise will augment the amount of fat used during the cardio workout because the strength training will deplete the muscles’ store of carbohydrates (glycogen).[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="Do I Need to Take Dietary Supplements?" tab_id="1461246432070-12081c76-29e4"][vc_column_text]Your clients do not need dietary supplements unless they have a documented vitamin deficiency or they do not eat a balanced diet. Using supplements as an alternative to a sound diet can lead to serious deficits in the consumption of other nutrients (Benardot et al. 2001).[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="What Is My Target Heart Rate?" tab_id="1461247989250-10fb4e26-f6a4"][vc_column_text]Target heart rate—the heart rate range used to determine the desired intensity of an activity—will differ depending on the goal of the workout. You can calculate target heart rate using a percentage of your client’s heart rate maximum (HRmax), which can be predicted by subtracting your client’s age from 220, or by measuring your client’s heart rate while he or she performs a maximum exercise test.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="What Is the Difference Between Weight Machines and Free Weights?" tab_id="1461247990457-54be2209-eaea"][vc_column_text]Ignoring the effect of gravity in creating resistance during all movements, free weights (dumbbells) keep the resistance on the muscle constant throughout the joint’s range of motion (ROM), while weight machines use variable resistance, with the resistance changing throughout the ROM.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="Why Are My Muscles Sore After a Workout?" tab_id="1461247991727-4e7f116a-da0b"][vc_column_text]Soreness results from high force production when an exercise is new or a load is greater than normal. Furthermore, eccentric muscle contractions (in which the muscle lengthens, as when lowering a weight) cause more soreness in the days following the workout than either isometric contractions (in which the muscle does not change length, as when holding a weight) or concentric contractions (in which the muscle shortens, as when lifting a weight).[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="How Do I Get Rid of These Flabby Arms?" tab_id="1461247993069-536e7844-5601"][vc_column_text]One of the biggest exercise myths is that you can lose fat in an area of the body by strength training or exercising that specific body part. The truth is that “spot reducing” and “spot toning” do not work, because we cannot dictate from where our bodies will decide to oxidize fat, nor can we change fat into muscle.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section title="How Often Should I Work Out/Lift Weights?" tab_id="1461247994108-ba34c455-9bc3"][vc_column_text]According to the American College of Sports Medicine (ACSM), your clients should exercise 20 to 60 minutes, three to five days a week for health/fitness promotion (ACSM 1995). Exercising only three days a week may be enough for previously sedentary clients to improve their fitness, but it will take more exercise to see further improvements.[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][/vc_tta_accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row]

item.title: Rebecca Payne
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
[vc_row][vc_column width="1/2"][mybroker_table striped="1" bordered="1" hover="1" responsive="1"]
Name Rebecca Payne
Age: 23
Status: Single
Occupation: Manager
Location: London, U.K.
Height: 5'6"
Starting weight: 265
Current weight: 205
Starting waist size: 39"
Current waist size: 34"
[/mybroker_table][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/2"][vc_single_image image="2539" img_size="full"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][ultimate_spacer height="30" height_on_tabs="30" height_on_tabs_portrait="30" height_on_mob_landscape="30" height_on_mob="30"][ultimate_heading main_heading="The Lifestyle" main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I grew up eating fast food and Chinese food and drinking tons of soda. I was always on the chubby side, but I played volleyball and danced, and I was happy.   My weight hovered in the 215 pounds until I got pregnant. I gained 50 pounds, but lost most of it by walking with my stroller after I had my son. But when I got pregnant again a year later, my weight shot back up and stayed there.   I felt so uncomfortable in my body. My feet were swollen all the time and I often woke up gasping for air in the middle of the night.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="45" height_on_tabs="45" height_on_tabs_portrait="45" height_on_mob_landscape="45" height_on_mob="45"][ultimate_heading main_heading="The change" main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I decided to cut out soda and fast food, and tried to follow the Paleo diet. I wanted to change immediately.   I ate super healthy for a few days—chicken, vegetables—but eventually I crashed and ate everything in sight. I tried to follow workout DVDs at home, but I quit when I didn’t see any results.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][mybroker_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

The number on the scale kept creeping up.

[/mybroker_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][ultimate_heading main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I also stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday to justify having a lazy, junk-filled weekend. I realized that if I wanted to make a change, I had to start that day.   I began meal prepping on Sundays, ditched the strict rules of Paleo, and went for healthy snacks like celery and hummus. I got back to the gym and did workouts that I used to do for softball in college. I lifted weights and did intervals on the treadmill. What began as two or three gym sessions a week became five. I even started swimming for extra cardio.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][mybroker_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

I stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday.

[/mybroker_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]After a year, I’d lost almost 50 pounds. I went back for my checkup, excited about the progress I’d made. But my doctor was concerned about my fluttering heart rate, which was something I’d brushed off. After three months of doctors and tests, I was diagnosed with supraventricular tachycardia, which means that my heartbeat was irregular because of an extra nerve passageway in my heart. I was a ticking time bomb for a heart attack.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][ult_hotspot Modal windows are often called heavy windows or modal dialogs because the window is often used to display a dialog box. Modal windows are commonly used in GUI systems to command user awareness and to display emergency states, although they have been argued to be ineffective for that use. item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:
Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)
...or something like this:
The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.
As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.excerpt:encoded: To take a trivial example, which of us ever undertakes laborious physical exercise, except to obtain some advantage from it? But who has any right to find fault with a man who chooses to enjoy a pleasure that has no annoying consequences, or one who avoids a pain that produces no resultant pleasure?

sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I decided to cut out soda and fast food, and tried to follow the Paleo diet. I wanted to change immediately.   I ate super healthy for a few days—chicken, vegetables—but eventually I crashed and ate everything in sight. I tried to follow workout DVDs at home, but I quit when I didn’t see any results.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

The number on the scale kept creeping up.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][ultimate_heading main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I also stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday to justify having a lazy, junk-filled weekend. I realized that if I wanted to make a change, I had to start that day.   I began meal prepping on Sundays, ditched the strict rules of Paleo, and went for healthy snacks like celery and hummus. I got back to the gym and did workouts that I used to do for softball in college. I lifted weights and did intervals on the treadmill. What began as two or three gym sessions a week became five. I even started swimming for extra cardio.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

I stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]After a year, I’d lost almost 50 pounds. I went back for my checkup, excited about the progress I’d made. But my doctor was concerned about my fluttering heart rate, which was something I’d brushed off. After three months of doctors and tests, I was diagnosed with supraventricular tachycardia, which means that my heartbeat was irregular because of an extra nerve passageway in my heart. I was a ticking time bomb for a heart attack.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]

I tried to follow workout DVDs at home, but I quit when I didn’t see any results.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

The number on the scale kept creeping up.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][ultimate_heading main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I also stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday to justify having a lazy, junk-filled weekend. I realized that if I wanted to make a change, I had to start that day.   I began meal prepping on Sundays, ditched the strict rules of Paleo, and went for healthy snacks like celery and hummus. I got back to the gym and did workouts that I used to do for softball in college. I lifted weights and did intervals on the treadmill. What began as two or three gym sessions a week became five. I even started swimming for extra cardio.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

I stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]After a year, I’d lost almost 50 pounds. I went back for my checkup, excited about the progress I’d made. But my doctor was concerned about my fluttering heart rate, which was something I’d brushed off. After three months of doctors and tests, I was diagnosed with supraventricular tachycardia, which means that my heartbeat was irregular because of an extra nerve passageway in my heart. I was a ticking time bomb for a heart attack.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]

[/startup_pro_table][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/2"][vc_single_image image="2539" img_size="full"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][ultimate_spacer height="30" height_on_tabs="30" height_on_tabs_portrait="30" height_on_mob_landscape="30" height_on_mob="30"][ultimate_heading main_heading="The Lifestyle" main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I grew up eating fast food and Chinese food and drinking tons of soda. I was always on the chubby side, but I played volleyball and danced, and I was happy.   My weight hovered in the 215 pounds until I got pregnant. I gained 50 pounds, but lost most of it by walking with my stroller after I had my son. But when I got pregnant again a year later, my weight shot back up and stayed there.   I felt so uncomfortable in my body. My feet were swollen all the time and I often woke up gasping for air in the middle of the night.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="45" height_on_tabs="45" height_on_tabs_portrait="45" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I decided to cut out soda and fast food, and tried to follow the Paleo diet. I wanted to change immediately.   I ate super healthy for a few days—chicken, vegetables—but eventually I crashed and ate everything in sight. I tried to follow workout DVDs at home, but I quit when I didn’t see any results.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

The number on the scale kept creeping up.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][ultimate_heading main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I also stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday to justify having a lazy, junk-filled weekend. I realized that if I wanted to make a change, I had to start that day.   I began meal prepping on Sundays, ditched the strict rules of Paleo, and went for healthy snacks like celery and hummus. I got back to the gym and did workouts that I used to do for softball in college. I lifted weights and did intervals on the treadmill. What began as two or three gym sessions a week became five. I even started swimming for extra cardio.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

I stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]After a year, I’d lost almost 50 pounds. I went back for my checkup, excited about the progress I’d made. But my doctor was concerned about my fluttering heart rate, which was something I’d brushed off. After three months of doctors and tests, I was diagnosed with supraventricular tachycardia, which means that my heartbeat was irregular because of an extra nerve passageway in my heart. I was a ticking time bomb for a heart attack.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]

[/startup_pro_table][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/2"][vc_single_image image="2739" img_size="full"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][ultimate_spacer height="30" height_on_tabs="30" height_on_tabs_portrait="30" height_on_mob_landscape="30" height_on_mob="30"][ultimate_heading main_heading="The Lifestyle" main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I grew up eating fast food and Chinese food and drinking tons of soda. I was always on the chubby side, but I played volleyball and danced, and I was happy.   My weight hovered in the 215 pounds until I got pregnant. I gained 50 pounds, but lost most of it by walking with my stroller after I had my son. But when I got pregnant again a year later, my weight shot back up and stayed there.   I felt so uncomfortable in my body. My feet were swollen all the time and I often woke up gasping for air in the middle of the night.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="45" height_on_tabs="45" height_on_tabs_portrait="45" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I decided to cut out soda and fast food, and tried to follow the Paleo diet. I wanted to change immediately.   I ate super healthy for a few days—chicken, vegetables—but eventually I crashed and ate everything in sight. I tried to follow workout DVDs at home, but I quit when I didn’t see any results.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

The number on the scale kept creeping up.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][ultimate_heading main_heading_color="#444444" sub_heading_color="#5e5e5e" alignment="left" main_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans|variant:600" main_heading_style="font-weight:600;" main_heading_font_size="desktop:24px;" main_heading_line_height="desktop:29px;" sub_heading_font_family="font_family:Open Sans|font_call:Open+Sans" sub_heading_font_size="desktop:16px;" sub_heading_line_height="desktop:26px;" main_heading_margin="margin-bottom:15px;"]I also stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday to justify having a lazy, junk-filled weekend. I realized that if I wanted to make a change, I had to start that day.   I began meal prepping on Sundays, ditched the strict rules of Paleo, and went for healthy snacks like celery and hummus. I got back to the gym and did workouts that I used to do for softball in college. I lifted weights and did intervals on the treadmill. What began as two or three gym sessions a week became five. I even started swimming for extra cardio.[/ultimate_heading][ultimate_spacer height="25" height_on_tabs="25" height_on_tabs_portrait="25" height_on_mob_landscape="25" height_on_mob="25"][startup_pro_blockquote border_color="#2ecc71"]

I stopped telling myself I would start eating healthy and work out on Monday.

[/startup_pro_blockquote][ultimate_spacer height="15" height_on_tabs="15" height_on_tabs_portrait="15" height_on_mob_landscape="15" height_on_mob="15"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]After a year, I’d lost almost 50 pounds. I went back for my checkup, excited about the progress I’d made. But my doctor was concerned about my fluttering heart rate, which was something I’d brushed off. After three months of doctors and tests, I was diagnosed with supraventricular tachycardia, which means that my heartbeat was irregular because of an extra nerve passageway in my heart. I was a ticking time bomb for a heart attack.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]
